EM_0006|Lu-177|Which major emission is correct?|Beta-minus particles plus low-energy gamma photons|Lu-177 is primarily a beta-minus therapeutic radionuclide and also emits low-energy gamma photons such as approximately 113 and 208 keV which allow imaging and dosimetry.|2|beta_minus_low_energy_gamma
EM_0007|Y-90|Which major emission is correct?|High-energy beta-minus particles|Y-90 is primarily a high-energy beta-minus emitter. It is used therapeutically and does not have a strong primary gamma emission for conventional imaging.|1|high_energy_beta_minus
EM_0008|Ra-223|Which major emission is correct?|Alpha particles|Ra-223 is an alpha-emitting therapeutic radionuclide. Its alpha particles have high linear energy transfer and short tissue range.|1|alpha
EM_0009|Rb-82|Which major emission is correct?|Positron emission with 511 keV annihilation photons|Rb-82 is a positron emitter used for PET myocardial perfusion imaging. Its positron emission leads to 511 keV annihilation photons.|1|positron_511
EM_0010|C-11|Which major emission is correct?|Positron emission with 511 keV annihilation photons|C-11 is a positron emitter used for PET imaging. The detected signal comes from paired 511 keV annihilation photons.|2|positron_511
EM_0011|N-13|Which major emission is correct?|Positron emission with 511 keV annihilation photons|N-13 is a positron emitter used for PET imaging such as N-13 ammonia myocardial perfusion imaging.|2|positron_511
EM_0012|O-15|Which major emission is correct?|Positron emission with 511 keV annihilation photons|O-15 is a positron emitter used for specialized PET applications. Its very short half-life requires on-site cyclotron production.|3|positron_511
EM_0013|In-111|Which major emission is correct?|171 and 245 keV gamma photons|In-111 emits gamma photons commonly listed around 171 and 245 keV. These emissions allow gamma camera imaging but with higher energy than Tc-99m.|2|gamma_171_245
EM_0014|Tl-201|Which major emission is correct?|Mercury x-rays around 69 to 83 keV|Tl-201 imaging primarily uses characteristic mercury x-rays around 69 to 83 keV. It also has gamma emissions but the low-energy x-rays are classically tested.|2|mercury_xray_69_83
EM_0015|Ga-67|Which major emission is correct?|Gamma photons around 93, 185, and 300 keV|Ga-67 emits multiple gamma photons including approximately 93, 185, and 300 keV. This multi-energy emission profile is important for gamma camera imaging.|2|gamma_93_185_300
EM_0016|Xe-133|Which major emission is correct?|81 keV gamma photon with beta-minus emission|Xe-133 decays by beta-minus emission and emits an 81 keV gamma photon useful for ventilation imaging.|2|beta_minus_gamma_81
